The code violates the Open-Closed Principle (OCP). The OCP states that software entities should be open for extension but closed for modification. In this case, if we want to add a new type of bird, we would have to modify the Bird class or create a new subclass which is not ideal as it violates the OCP principle.

To refactor the code to comply with the Open-Closed Principle, we can introduce an interface for birds that includes methods related to flight and running capabilities:

```java
public interface FlyingBird {
    void fly();
    double getFlightSpeed();
}

public interface RunningBird {
    void run();
    double getRunningSpeed();
}
```
Then, we can modify the Bird class to implement these interfaces:

```java
public abstract class Bird implements FlyingBird, RunningBird {
    protected String species;
    protected double wingSpan;

    public Bird(String species, double wingSpan)  {
        this.species = species;
        this.wingSpan = wingSpan;
    }

    public String getSpecies()  {
        return species;
    }

    public double getWingSpan()  {
        return wingSpan;
    }
}
```
And modify the Eagle, Hummingbird and Ostrich classes to implement these interfaces:

```java
public class Eagle extends Bird implements FlyingBird {
    // ...
}

public class Hummingbird extends Bird implements FlyingBird {
    // ...
}

public class Ostrich extends Bird implements RunningBird {
    // ...
}
```
Finally, we can modify the FlightSimulator class to use these interfaces:

```java
public class FlightSimulator  {
    public void simulateFlight(FlyingBird bird, double distance)  {
        System.out.println("Starting flight simulation for " + bird.getSpecies());
        bird.fly();
        double speed = bird.getFlightSpeed();
        double time = distance / speed;
        System.out.println("Flight time: " + time + " hours for " + distance + " km");
    }

    public void simulateRunning(RunningBird bird, double distance)  {
        System.out.println("Starting running simulation for " + bird.getSpecies());
        bird.run();
        double speed = bird.getRunningSpeed();
        double time = distance / speed;
        System.out.println("Running time: " + time + " hours for " + distance + " km");
    }

    public void compareFlightCapabilities(Bird[] birds, double testDistance)  {
        for (Bird bird : birds)  {
            if (bird instanceof FlyingBird)  {
                simulateFlight((FlyingBird) bird, testDistance);
            } else if (bird instanceof RunningBird)  {
                simulateRunning((RunningBird) bird, testDistance);
            }
            System.out.println("---");
        }
    }
}
```
This way, we can add new types of birds without modifying the existing code and still comply with the Open-Closed Principle.

